loci-parsing refactor

- LociParser → ParsedLoci, removed state+mutation pattern, leaving an
  object that just wraps loci, after we've parsed strings, but before
  we have contig-lengths / a LociSet
  - uses ParsedLociRange and ParsedLociRanges classes, which
    encapsulate "all loci" special-casing.
  - parseLoci method is moved in there, since it's basically a
    constructor for a ParsedLoci.
- removed all non-test calls of unsafe ParsedLoci.result and
  LociSet(String), that assume no contig-lengths are needed because
  provided ranges will be closed.
- changed some callers to reflect that the ReadSets() call now
  integrates building loci and filters in addition to loading
  read-sets.
- move a couple of InputFilters ctors that were only used in tests to
  TestInputFilters

LociMap Contig ctors

loadLoci rename, Common, PFMU nits

Improve LociSet.take implementation, resolve TODO

- Build two LociSets out of existing Contigs, splitting <= 1 Contig
  into two pieces.
- Delegate LociSet.take() implementation to LociSet Contig.take().
- Rename LociSet Builder to LociParser; move it toward primarily
  handling parsing string representations of genomic intervals, and
  requiring contig lengths to produce a LociSet.
- Create a new LociSet Builder that accumulates fully-formed Contigs
- Push LociMap.inverse logic into per-Contig inversions.
LociMap Contig: add convenience ctors
LociMap rename asInverseMap to inverse
LociSet: add convenience ctors, rm empty

set.Builder: privatize put() implementation

Expose convenience wrappers.

set.Builder: result() wrappers

make result() implementation private, provide three convenience
wrappers around it.

map.Contig: remove superfluous methods

contains, count, ranges, numRanges, isEmpty, lociIndividually, union
LociSet: rm equals,hashCode,newBuilder,unused ctor
LociMap rm equals, hashCode, empty, .union

separate Loci{Set,Map} implementations

- LociSet wraps its own SortedMap[String, Contig]
- set and map contigs are exposed directly for simpler caller
  traversals
- .take() is implemented on LociSet, which is logically what it is
  called on, instead of on LociMap
- remove .toString indirection wrt including values vs. not
LociMap: generalize serde to all types
LociSet+Builder: ctors, remove LociSet.parse
LociMap: add convenience ctor/apply
LociSet, Builder "all" helpers

move Loci{Set,Map} into pkgs, split out classes

classes in addition to the Loci{Set,Map} that is the main attraction.

Change Seq to Vector and other small fixes

 * Change Seq to Vector in a number of places. For vast majority of cases, Vector performs better. Where possible, we use Vector for concreteness but in some places, especially deserialization, it's desirable to be able to pass Arrays around without copying them to a Vector. In these places, we use IndexedSeq.
 * Also change per-sample Seq's to be of type PerSample in a few places
 * Add isClipped method to Alignment
 * Small comment updates

Replace LociInWindowsIterator

This commit drops the LociInWindowsIterator class, adds the
SlidingWindow.advanceMultiple function as a replacement, and modifies
DistributedUtil to use this function.

The primary motivation for this is readability, but there is also a subtle bug
fix here.  The hasNext() function on LociInWindowsIterator wasn't correct in
general, since if skipEmpty=true, then it is impossible to know whether there
are really more regions available to advance to without actually doing the
advancing. (For example, suppose we have a window at locus 100, the next region
to be read by that window is at locus 150, and we want to advance to position
1000. It is impossible to know if there are in fact regions at locus 1000
without first advancing through the region at locus 150.)

Closes #214.

Refactor likelihood calculation

This commit moves the likelihood calculation code from Pileup and Genotype into
a new singleton object.

This refactoring enables a more efficient implementation that resuses
computation between genotypes that share alleles. On my local tests, the
likelihood calculation is about 40% faster than the previous implementation.
Overall that gives about a 10% performance boost to variant calling.

 * Create a new package and singleton object Likelihood for likelihood calculation code.
 * Remove likelihood calculation code from Pileup and Genotype
 * Port tests from PileupLikelihoodSuite and GenotypeSuite into a new test suite LikelihoodSuite
 * Port variant callers to use new likelihood calculation function.

Speedup Pileup.atGreaterLocus by using a vector for PileupElement

Seq in scala defaults to a List implementation, which takes O(n) time for
append. This commit changes Pileup to use a Vector-backed Seq for PileupElement
instances, which makes Pileup.atGreaterLocus much faster. The interface to
Pileup stays the same.

On my single-node tests, this gives about about a 20% speedup in overall
variant calling time (on one test: 5 min 7 sec -> 3 min 55 sec).

Merge pull request #105 from hammerlab/upgrades-and-optimizations

Performance improvements, code refactoring, and upgrade to Spark 1.0.
address minor issues raised in code review
fix failing unit test

Performance improvements, code refactoring, and upgrade to Spark 1.0.

Initial goal here was just to be able to run on chr20 without specifying -loci argument and still have things work (i.e. don't have two tasks stuck looking at other contigs that don't have reads). That ended up expanding into a number performance improvements, refactorings, dependency upgrades, and code fixes.

Major changes:

 * Much more efficient handling of the reads assigned to each task. We used to filter an unsorted iterator of reads into iterators over each contig, and then sort. This resulted in many traversals of the reads. Now we sort first and then walk through the reads only once.
 * Upgrade to Spark 1.0, Java 7, and ADAM 0.11.1-SNAPSHOT. We can move off ADAM snapshot to a real release once ADAM has a release that uses Spark 1.0

Minor changes:

 * Fix issues involved in Spark upgrade: move hadoop dependency to end of pom, call setReferences(true) in Kryo initialization to avoid infinite recursion.
 * Introduce ReadSet for keeping track of read metadata (e.g. sequence dictionaries) with the RDD[Read] instance.
 * paritionLociByApproximateReadDepth now has special handling of contigs with no reads mapped for better efficiency. Unit tests.
 * pileupFlatMap and variants now have a 'skipEmpty' option, which, if set, will result in skipping loci where no reads align. This can be an important optimization when running over e.g. many contigs that have no reads mapped. Add 'nextStartLocus' method to SlidingReadWindow to enable an efficient implementation of this.
 * SlidingReadWindow: more efficient setCurrentLocus implementation.
 * Minor convenience functions added to LociSet.

Merge pull request #79 from hammerlab/use_guacamole_read_instead_of_adamrecord_squashed1

Performance improvement by replacing ADAMRecord with the classes defined in Read.scala.

This commit gets a substantial performance improvement by replacing ADAMRecord with the classes defined in Read.scala.

These homegrown Read classes avoid implicit conversions, lazy vals, unused fields, and as much indirection as possible.

Limitation: Currently we do not support loading ADAM data. That will come later in a separate PR.

* Added a Read trait, and MappedRead and UnmappedRead case classes that implement it.
* Load Reads using hadoop-bam directly. ADAM loading for BAMs is inefficient: parses fields twice.
* Instead of String and Char for nucleotide bases, use Byte and Array[Byte]. Add Bases.scala: functions for manipulating sequences.
* String fields in Read objects (sample name, reference name) are interned.
* Drop support for '-loci mapped' commandline argument. Now must either analyze all loci ('-loci all') or a specific set of them ('-loci chr1:100-200,...')
* Use SequenceDictionary instances to get contigs, instead of a distributed reduction on the reads.
* Fix bug in scripts/guacamole-demeter that had it ignoring $SPARK_JAVA_OPTS
